04294nam a22006375i 9781503633957DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036339577 a10.1515/97815036339572doi  a(DE-B1597)642274  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPR448.C34bH36 2023 7aLIT0041802bisacsh04a820.9/3553223/eng/202207271 aHanson, Lenora, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Romantic Rhetoric of Accumulation /cLenora Hanson. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Romantic Rhetoric of Accumulation -- tCHAPTER 1 Apostrophe and Riot -- tCHAPTER 2 Anachronism, Dreams, and Enclosure -- tCHAPTER 3 Tautology, Witchcraft, and a Thingly Commons -- tCHAPTER 4 Figure, Space, and Race between 1769 and 1985 -- tCoda: Rhetorical Reading toward a Global Romanticism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Romantic Rhetoric of Accumulation provides an account of the long arc of dispossession from the British Romantic period to today. Lenora Hanson glimpses histories of subsistence (such as reproductive labor, vagrancy and criminality, and unwaged labor) as figural ways of living that are superfluous—simultaneously more than enough to live and less than what is necessary for capitalism. Hanson treats rhetorical language as an archive of capital's accumulation through dispossession, in works by S.T. Coleridge, Edmund Burke, Mary Robinson, William Wordsworth, Benjamin Moseley, Joseph Priestley, and Alexander von Humboldt, as well as in contemporary film and critical theory. Reading riots through apostrophe, enclosure through anachronism, superstition and witchcraft through tautology, and the paradoxical coincidence of subsistence living with industrialization, Hanson shows the figural to be a material record of the survival of non-capitalist forms of life within capitalism. But this survival is not always-already resistant to capitalism, nor are the origins of capital accumulation confined to the Romantic past. Hanson reveals rhetorical figure as entwined in deeply ambivalent ways with the circuitous, ongoing process of dispossession. Reading both historically and rhetorically, Hanson argues that rhetorical language records histories of dispossession and the racialized, gendered distribution of the labor of subsistence. Romanticism, they show, is more contemporary than ever.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aCapitalism in literature. 0aDiscourse analysis, Literary. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh  aDispossession.  aGender.  aMarxist Theory.  aPrimitive Accumulation.  aRace.  aRhetoric.  aRhetorical Figure.  aRhetorical Reading.  aRomanticism.  aSubsistence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363395740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633957423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503633957/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles